    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-01T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-01T03:00:00-05:00" n="21"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a5/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-01T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >February 1, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 1—6:24 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>21. Yesterday in the Diet Foreign Minister Hirota stated in effect: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Japan’s policy toward the second Washington conference<note n="32"
                                xml:id="d21fn32">The first Washington Conference, from November 1921
                                to February 1922, dealt with naval armaments and with Far Eastern
                                questions; for correspondence, see <ref target="frus1922v01#pg_1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 1</ref> ff.</note> has not yet
                            been decided but in regard to the naval ratio question I doubt whether
                            it is rational to limit naval strength by ratios. It is also very
                            doubtful whether a disarmament agreement based on ratios will contribute
                            to world peace.</p>
                        <p>As regards Manchuria I believe that question is a closed issue and truly
                            cannot imagine that it would become a source of controversy at the
                            conference.</p>
                        <pb facs="0114" n="24" xml:id="pg_24"/>
                        <p>The mandate islands which should naturally have become Japanese territory
                            were obtained under mandate because of the circumstances at Versailles.
                            That Japan should lose her rights because of withdrawal from the League
                            is untenable.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
